WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
In this video, we’ll be talking about how
you can make sure that the materials you

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:09.000
create are accessible for everyone. A lot of
the time when we talk about

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:14.000
free content online like OER, we say that
it’s accessible because you can literally
“access” it,

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.000
but today’s video is not about whether you
can click through to read a news article or

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:23.000
look at social media posts without logging
in. No, this video is about digital
accessibility,

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:28.000
or the set of processes and practices that
you can use to make sure that anyone in your
potential

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:31.000
audience can fully engage with your work
online.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Making your work accessible helps every
possible downstream user who

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
might want to access it, have a better
chance of learning and benefiting from what
you’ve created.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:42.000
This is especially important for open
content,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
because anyone in the world can technically
access your work,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
but we want everyone to also be able to get
the same value out of that material.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
Plus, making your work accessible helps
those readers, listeners, and others

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.000
to feel included and to know that their
needs are being considered by peers like you

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
who are creating and sharing content for
free online.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Remember: everyone benefits here:

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Creating educational podcasts with
downloadable transcripts can be useful both

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.000
for listeners who prefer to read along or
take notes on what they’re listening to,

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
and for those who are hard of hearing or
deaf.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And using headings in your text-based
projects makes it easier for sighted users
to skim through

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
the sections you included and get an
overview of your content, while also
providing more context

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:25.000
for those who need to use a screen reader to
interpret the text you’ve shared online.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:29.000
So, how do you make your projects
accessible?

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:33.000
The Web content accessibility guidelines
include a really useful set of principles
for tracking

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
digital accessibility: they say that content
should be Perceivable, Operable,
Understandable,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.000
and Robust (which nicely translates down to
the acronym POUR). Let’s go through these
together,

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:49.000
and talk about specific tips for how you can
meet these principles in your own work:

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
First, content should be Perceivable: or,
users should be able to actually

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
perceive the content in some way. For
example, if a reader can’t physically

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:01.000
see the text on a page, that text should be
presented in basic formatting that allows a

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:06.000
screen reader to “read off” the text
audibly. If there are a lot of images in the
text,

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:10.000
alternative text and captions should provide
enough context for readers to understand

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
everything presented within that image. For
videos, you might provide captions for

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
those who can’t otherwise perceive the
audible aspects of your video.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And for podcasts or audio-heavy video
projects, you might also provide a
transcript with headings

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:27.000
and speaker tags so your audience can follow
along with who is speaking and how the
content

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:30.000
of your podcast or video is organized.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
Next, content should be Operable: or, users
should be able to navigate, interface with,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:37.000
and properly process your content.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
For text-based projects, this is usually
handled through headings, which provide
structure and

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.000
outline to your text visually, while also
serving as a machine readable outline for
screen readers.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
You don’t want to just make text 24 point
font and bold to make it look like a
heading:

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
you should also use the actual heading tools
built into your word processor of choice

00:02:55.000 --> 00:03:01.000
to denote what the sections in your text
are. For audio and video projects, this
might mean

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:06.000
you put in pauses so your audience has time
to process and engage with your material… or
it could

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:10.000
be as simple as using a tool to share your
work that allows pausing, rewinding, and
navigating

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:15.000
through sections... Sort of like when you’re
listening to a Youtube video, and you
realize

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
you lost track of where you are, so you hit
the “go back 5 seconds” button to rewind a
bit.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And then there are links! When you share
links out to other places in a text
document, you should

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.000
use descriptive links, or in other words,
the linked text should describe where the
link goes.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.000
A “click here” link doesn’t really help
people understand what they’re clicking on,

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
and for folks who use screen readers, they
have an option to read off all the links on
a page.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
If all of the links say “click here,” that’s
even more confusing than it is helpful.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Instead, have a descriptive link like "here
is a link to our blog " or

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
"read up on the topic of accessible
content."

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:57.000
After Operable, we have “Understandable”
content: or,

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:01.000
you should present information in a way that
your users are able to understand.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Sounds simple, right? This might have to do
with the content itself or the interface
it’s presented within.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
The biggest point here for your OER projects
I want to focus on is content level:

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:16.000
who is your audience? What is their
education level? And how can you make sure
that the information you share

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
is clear, understandable, and has a solid
enough scope for your audience to understand
what

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:27.000
is being communicated? You don’t have to
make everything understandable to everyone;
however,

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:32.000
thinking about who your major audience is
and what context they need in order to
appreciate

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
your work? That’s pretty important.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
And finally, content should be Robust: or,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
various tools and assistive technologies
should be able to “read” your work.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Remember how I mentioned using headings and
descriptive links to help screen readers
parse

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.000
out what your documents say? That is part of
this section as well.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Make sure that the alternative text you
provide for images in your documents

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:59.000
actually describes the purpose of the image
it stands in for, and if the image is too
large,

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
be sure to provide a longer image
description in the text surrounding it. For
example,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:08.000
if you have an image that shows a process
like mitosis in action, you’d want to
describe that

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.000
process, the steps, and what it looks like
in simple text as well, both to supplement

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:18.000
the alternative text for the image, and to
help explain what is going on in the image
in general.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
For headings, I already mentioned that you
should use the heading tool built into

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.000
your word processor to mark where headings
are.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:28.000
But you also want to make sure that the
headings follow a logical order.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
If I have a grocery list and the title
"grocery list" is a heading 1, for example,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
the section for produce should be a heading
2, and the section for fruits should be a
heading 3

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
under that. If I want to go communicate that
a heading is of the same level as another,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:47.000
like boxed goods in contrast to produce, I
would set boxed goods to Heading 2 as well.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
Robust is really the section for “do what we
said in the other sections, and do it

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
well,” so when you’re thinking about making
your content accessible in a way that is
also robust,

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
remember you can get help here.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:02.000
So! Now that we’ve gone over the 4 sections
of POUR,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:07.000
what can you do to make sure you’re being
accessible with your projects? Here are some
general tips:

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:12.000
First, start with an outline, a script, or
another way of keeping yourself on task with
your project.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
This can help you put together good section
headings or

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:19.000
otherwise just have a solid outline that
your audience can follow along with.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:23.000
Second, keep in mind accessibility from the
start of your project. Don’t wait until the

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:27.000
end to fix all your links and check that
your headings follow each other logically.
If you

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.000
start out with the POUR tips in mind, you’ll
save yourself a lot of work down the road.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:37.000
Next, make sure that you actually create
captions or transcripts for any media
projects. You might

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
create these from your base script that I
mentioned earlier, or you might need to

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:45.000
draft them from scratch. But don’t forget
them! Auto-generated captions are not good
enough,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:51.000
especially if your project is focusing on a
scientific topic that uses subject specific
terms.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:55.000
And remember, you can always ask for help!
There are great support people in your
department,

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
in your library, and elsewhere on your
college campus that can support you with
making sure your

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
work is accessible from the start. So don’t
feel like you have to do this all alone.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
You don't!

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Thank you for watching! You can find
additional readings and resources for
creating accessible

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
materials in the description below,
including handouts, videos, and webpages
I’ve compiled for

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:22.000
you. This video by Abbey Elder is available
